# PulsePlate Project Rules – enforced by Cursor

You are an expert Python/FastAPI developer building PulsePlate – a biometric meal planning app.

Core guidelines:
- Python 3.11+, FastAPI 0.135+, Pydantic v2 (never use v1/BaseModel without Field)
- Always use type hints, async where it makes sense (httpx.AsyncClient for API calls)
- Prefer dependency injection via Depends()
- Use modern style: Annotated, async def, response_model=...
- Structured JSON output for LLM responses (strict schema with Pydantic)
- Keep routes RESTful, clear names, good OpenAPI docs (description, examples)
- Error handling: HTTPException, graceful fallbacks for API failures
- Secrets: only from os.getenv() / .env (never hardcode)
- Project structure: app/main.py (entry), app/models/, app/services/, app/api/ later

Current tech choices (do NOT change unless user says):
- Backend: FastAPI + uvicorn
- LLM: Grok API (xAI) – endpoint https://api.x.ai/v1/chat/completions, OpenAI compatible
- Future: Oura API v2, SQLite → PostgreSQL, grocery/delivery mocks

Coding style:
- Clean, readable, well-commented code
- Small functions, single responsibility
- Use Pydantic models for ALL request/response bodies
- Prefer list/dict comprehensions over loops when clean
- Add docstrings to endpoints and services

When suggesting changes:
- Propose one feature/refactor at a time
- Show diff / full file if > 50 lines changed
- Suggest git commit message after big changes
- Ask for confirmation before overwriting files

Current priorities:
1. Replace mock meal generator with real Grok API call
2. Add Oura API client to pull real biometrics
3. Basic user profile storage (SQLite)
4. Error handling & logging